'''Season 2009&ndash;10''' for [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] will be their eleventh consecutive season of play in the [[Scottish Premier League]]. The SPL season began on 15 August 2009, with a 2&ndash;1 win against [[St. Mirren F.C.|St. Mirren]] at [[Easter Road|home]]. Hibs will also compete in the [[Scottish Cup 2009&ndash;10|Scottish Cup]], but were knocked out of the [[Scottish League Cup 2009&ndash;10|Scottish League Cup]] in the third round by [[St. Johnstone F.C.|St. Johnstone]].

==Pre-season==

[[Hibernian F.C.|Hibs]] initially confirmed seven [[friendly match]]es for pre-season, with two of those matches being billed as a ''"Hibernian XI"''.<ref>[http://www.hibs.co.uk/news/more.php?id=3470_0_1_0_C Preston North End to visit Easter Road], [[Hibernian F.C.]] official website.</ref> <ref>[http://www.hibs.co.uk/news/more.php?id=3457_0_1_0_C Hibernian Confirm Summer Irish Tour], [[Hibernian F.C.]] official website.</ref> Hibs played their first match on 15 July, winning 7&ndash;0 against [[Selkirk F.C.|Selkirk]].<ref>[http://sport.scotsman.com/football/New-boys-do-Hibs-boss.5465070.jp New boys do Hibs boss proud in goalfest], ''[[Edinburgh Evening News]]'', 16 July 2009.</ref> Hibs split their resources on 18 July, with a young side losing 4&ndash;2 at [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick]],<ref>[http://www.journallive.co.uk/newcastle-sports/football-news/non-league-football/2009/07/20/berwick-rangers-4-hibernian-xi-2-61634-24192320/ Berwick Rangers 4, Hibernian XI 2], ''Journal Live'', 20 July 2009.</ref> while a more experienced side won 4&ndash;0 at [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]].<ref>[http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/Dunfermline--0--4.5474993.jp Dunfermline 0&ndash;4 Hibs: Old guard still burning bright], ''[[Edinburgh Evening News]]'', 20 July 2009.</ref> [[John Hughes (footballer born 1964)|John Hughes]] only retained five players in the team that started against Dunfermline for the first team's next match, against [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]. Hibs were losing 1&ndash;0 when an [[electrical storm]] caused the [[Floodlights (sport)|floodlights]] to fail, prompting the referee David Somers to abandon the match after 46 minutes.<ref>[http://sport.scotsman.com/football/Raith-Rovers-1--0.5480702.jp Raith Rovers 1&ndash;0 Hibernian: Electrical storm stops play at Stark's], ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 22 July 2009.</ref>

Hibs then underwent a short Irish tour, winning 2&ndash;0 against [[IFA Premiership]] [[IFA Premiership 2008-09|champions]] [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]]. Two days later they lost 1&ndash;0 against a [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] side managed by former Hibs player [[Michael O'Neill (footballer)|Michael O'Neill]]. Hibs also lost their only pre-season game at [[Easter Road]], 3&ndash;1 against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 1 August. The game was a rematch of sorts for a match played in 1887 dubbed the ''Championship of the World'' by [[the Football Association]] and the [[Scottish Football Association]], as both clubs had won their respective national cup competitions that year.<ref>[http://www.hibs.co.uk/news/more.php?id=3472_0_1_0_C World Championship Re-Match], [[Hibernian F.C.]] official website.</ref> 

Hibs' final two matches of pre-season saw them play out goalless draws against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 5 August and against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], in a [[testimonial match]] for [[Jussi J<U+00E4><U+00E4>skel<U+00E4>inen]], on 8 August.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bolton_wanderers/8035945.stm Jaaskelainen lines up testimonial], [[BBC Sport]], 6 May 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.hibs.co.uk/news/comments.php?id=3606_0_1_0_C Reports: Bolton 0 Hibernian 0], [[Hibernian F.C.]] official website.</ref>

