==Transfers==
Hibs' first significant move in the close season was to part company with manager [[Mixu Paatelainen]], becoming the third [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] club to change manager in the space of a week.<ref name = "mixu">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hibernian/8074794.stm Paatelainen parts with Hibernian], [[BBC Sport]], 29 May 2009.</ref> [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] manager [[John Hughes (footballer born 1964)|John Hughes]] was immediately linked with the vacancy,<ref name = "mixu"/> and he was appointed Hibs manager 10 days later.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hibernian/8089954.stm Hughes appointed Hibernian boss], [[BBC Sport]], 8 June 2009.</ref>

Paatelainen had already begun making changes to the squad for the new season before he left, by releasing [[Fabi<U+00E1>n Yantorno]], [[Damon Gray]] and [[Andrew McNeil]].<ref name = "Hibs release"/><ref name = "released by Hibs"/> [[Grzegorz Szamotulski]]'s departure under free agency meant that Hughes needed to sign a new goalkeeper,<ref name = "released by Hibs"/> which he addressed by signing [[Graham Stack (footballer)|Graham Stack]]. Paatelainen had also done much of the work leading to the signing of [[Danny Galbraith]], which Hughes completed after he was appointed.<ref name = "aob"/>

There were two significant departures early in the summer, with Scotland international [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] moving to newly promoted [[Premier League]] club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], and club captain [[Rob Jones (footballer born 1979)|Rob Jones]] signing for [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref name = "guardian">[http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2009/aug/28/hibernian-john-hughes-anthony-stokes John Hughes' resurgent Hibernian face early test from Celtic], ''[[The Guardian]]'' Sport Blog.</ref> Both buying clubs broke their transfer fee record to secure their services.<ref name = "jones"/><ref name = "fletcher"/>

Hughes went back to his former club to sign [[midfielder]]s [[Patrick Cregg]] and [[Kevin McBride (footballer)|Kevin McBride]], with Cregg being his first signing as Hibs manager.<ref name = "cregg"/><ref name = "mcbride"/> Towards the end of the window, he made the "notable" signing of [[Anthony Stokes]], with the move going against a trend of SPL players moving to English clubs.<ref name = "guardian"/> Stokes had previously enjoyed a successful loan spell at Falkirk, where Hughes had also been his manager.

